The following query can be used to identify duplicate records in SQL tables: 

CREATE VIEW v_duplicates AS SELECT * FROM table1 t1 INNER JOIN (SELECT column1, MAX(column2) as maxval FROM table1 GROUP BY column1 ) m ON t1.column1 = m.maxval;

This view creates a temporary table which contains all rows from the original table along with their corresponding maximum value of another field. The join then takes place between this new table and the original one, resulting in only those records where the two fields have identical values being returned. This technique works well when both columns are numerical or date-time data types but it also works with text data types by converting them into numbers first using the CAST() function.

